It is a mistake to assume that Trump was subdued because of his disappointment over the mid-term election,
or that he lacked energy and enthusiasm because he was depressed about the results.   Rather, he was trying
to show his enemies within the Republican Party that he can play their game, and play it far better than they do.
He has done this before, notably when he met with Pres. L√≥pez Obrador of Mexico at the White House in July,
2020.  On that occasion, he behaved like a sober statesman while at the podium, as well as during their talks, 
even as he warned about illegal immigrants, the border wall, and "the danger to our country" posed by "hordes"
of thieves and drug addicts crossing the Rio Grande, before and after his sessions with Mexico's President, as
if he were Jekyll and Hyde, or an actor playing two diametrically opposite roles on screen, in rapid succession. 
In this case, Trump wants to prove that he can speak softly, yet still carry the biggest night stick on the block,
and that he can use the newly minted GOP rhetoric of 'bringing the country together' while doing his utmost 
to divide and destroy it.  Like a great basketball player who (as Wilt Chamberlain once did) plays 48 minutes
without taking a single shot from the field, just to demonstrate that he is more than a scoring machine (who
once scored 100 points in a single game), so too, Trump is determined to teach his rivals that he is both the
master of his fate and superior to them in every way, by keeping his ego in check just long enough to discuss
so-called issues, and by being soft rather than loud, calm rather than excited, and filled with love rather than
loaded with hate.  Granted, it doesn't quite work: even when Trump tries to be rational, he is prone to ranting,
whether it's about radical leftists or Chinese interference in the election.   Nor will it last.  He is too schizoid,
too maniacal and too mercurial to resist the temptation to go off on tangents, engage in temper tantrums,
and attack his opponents at every opportunity.  But then, Wilt Chamberlain (with whom Trump has nothing
else in common) didn't score just one point in an entire game (at the free throw line) more than once, either.  
Trump being Trump, he will soon return to bad form--indeed, he has never abandoned it.  Yet there's method
in his madness, even as there is sheer madness in his methods.  Like Ahab, Trump would strike the sun if it
insulted him, or even if it didn't.  His rage is boundless, and uncontrollable.   But he is determined to steer in
the direction he wants the ship of state to go, even if it means shipwreck for everyone on board.   Hence his 
mood is consistent, even as it rises and falls with the waves that engulf him, threatening to drown the crew.
His frustration notwithstanding, he knows his destiny, and is hell-bent on making it ours, with or without our
cooperation.  Hast seen the white whale?   That's what Trump is chasing; for in his obsession with gaining
revenge, he is willing to sweet-talk us to death, if only his electoral harpoon is long enough to make the kill.
